blueprint.description:
V2
Same as Item DropOff V2 just for input.
Moves Train Buffer, takes up more space but looks cleaner in my opinion.
Side note: V1 had a 4 train limit but if the output train buffer is full it will allow a train to get stuck in a wait split so I reduced it to 3 for better throughput and potentially prevent deadlocks.
V1
Buffers 3 input trains and 1 output. Takes 4 belts balanced into 6 then put in 2 cargo wagons.
blueprint.label: Item Pickup

blueprint.description:
V2
Same as Item Pickup V2 Just for output.
Flips input direction to match merger blueprint.
Moves Train Buffer, takes up more space but looks cleaner in my opinion.
Upgrades to 6-4 belt balancer.
Side note: V1 had a 4 train limit but if the output train buffer is full it will allow a train to get stuck in a wait split so I reduced it to 3 for better throughput and potentially prevent deadlocks.
V1
Buffers 3 input trains and 1 output. Takes two cargo wagons and merges them into 3 belts.
blueprint.label: Item Dropoff

blueprint.description:
V2
Just the 3 Way V2 but another output on the fourth side. Kind of pointless to have a dedicated blueprint for merging now.
V1
Brings two sides and brings them to the center and allows travel straight across.
blueprint.label: Merger

blueprint.description:
V2
Adds connection on the center two lanes for oncoming trains, might be slower on throughput but prevents trains getting stuck if input/output is set up wrong.
Fixed a signal and chain put in the wrong direction.
V1
adds two lanes on both sides and make all lanes one way by putting a signal before a chain signal
blueprint.label: Wait Split

blueprint.description:
V2
Brings the outside lane to one in the middle, joins the two center ones  then mirrored. Also connects the center to the farther perpendicular rail.
V1
Splits each track to connect to the other
blueprint.label: 3 Way

blueprint.description:
V2
Brings the outside lane to one in the middle, joins the two center ones  then mirrored. Also connects the center to the farther perpendicular rail.
V1
Tries to connect every individual track to to the other
blueprint.label: 4 Way

blueprint.description:
V1 
Just a basic through lane for trains that only have 1 cargo train between the two locomotives.
blueprint.label: Fuel 1-1-1-1

blueprint.description:
V2
Move the big power pole down, removing the medium one. 
Flipped power and boxes on the left to be centered.
V1
Puts fuel stops on the four tracks on both sides for whatever direction the train comes from. Since it’s built on the main line it was intended to allow a quick stop on the trains way but further testing seems to show it’s more officiant to not allow a through lane.
blueprint.label: Fuel 1-2-1
